> MANAGERS HOLD BACK FROM WINDOWS 4.0
--------------------------------------
Microsoft has overestimated IT managers' desire to move to Windows 4.0,
reports the IDG News Wire.
Recent surveys of IT managers show that users don't want to act as
extended beta sites for the first release of the 32-bit operating
system, known as Chicago, once it ships. They prefer to wait until its
stability is proven.
A report by analysts IDC said users are holding back for a variety of
reasons: only 41% have even migrated to Windows from DOS; they have not
yet gained returns on their Windows investments; they see no need to
upgrade Windows applications; they are reluctant to upgrade hardware to
run the new operating system; and they are still figuring out how to get
the existing technology to work.
Based on past experience with Windows and Windows NT, they do not
believe Microsoft will deliver a stable version of the operating system
first time out.
Chicago moved into full beta testing last month. It is Microsoft's
second attempt to provide a 32-bit upgrade to the DOS and Windows
operating environments. The first was Windows NT, whose first upgrade,
Daytona, is expected to ship this summer. Some users said it would take
them a year to ensure Chicago runs with their existing applications and
another two or three years to deploy it fully.
The US-based findings are backed by UK users' experience. Martin Telfer,
IT director at City solicitors Masons, a beta test site for Windows NT,
said: 'We will only move over when 32-bit applications arrive that offer
significant benefits to us. We are talking about next summer at the
earliest. Changing over to Chicago just to run Windows applications is
pointless.'
COMPUTING 7/7/94 P13

> APPLE PUTS ON THE POWER FOR TALIGENT
---------------------------------------
Apple Computer is planning a PowerPC-based Macintosh designed
specifically to run Tal OS, the Taligent Object Services environment,
reports the IDG News Wire.
The system, expected to be released by the end of 1995, is designed to
help software houses and corporate developers create Taligent-enabled
applications for Apple's next full version of its Mac operating system.
But the company's plans fall short of actually integrating the two
operating systems into a single environment.
Apple's difficulty implementing the Taligent technology is in stark
contrast to IBM, which has extensive plans to incorporate Taligent's
technology across all its platforms, from the desktop to the mainframe.
According to software developers familiar with Apple's plans, the
company is hedging its bets on how it will support the Taligent
environment. 'Apple's level of support does not match that of IBM. They
are nowhere near as committed,' one developer commented.
PowerOpen, a PowerPC version of IBM's AIX operating system, which
includes the Macintosh Applications Services module for running Mac
software, will support Tal Application Environment (Tal AE) immediately,
but Apple's mainstream operating system will not support Tal AE until
1996 at the earliest.
Taligent intends to ship the first release of Tal AE in the first half
of next year.Tal OS is currently scheduled to ship before the end of
1995.
Sources familiar with Apple's plans revealed that Apple is uncertain
about how to support the object-oriented operating system without
abandoning its own current operating system.
COMPUTING 7/7/94 P13

> IBM UNVEILS LATEST OS/2
-------------------------
IBM released the latest version of OS/2 last week, amid reports that
development of new versions of the operating system is behind schedule.
The company announced the multiprocessor version of the operating system
as the latest move in its plan to widen OS/2's appeal, and challenge
Windows and Windows NT.
Steve Walker, strategic advocate for IBM UK's personal software products
division, said the next move will be to release a 4Mb version of OS/2
and OS/2 for Windows capable of working on laptops. It will also release
an 8Mb version for PCs based on the PowerPC processor.
'We realised that for symmetric multiprocessing and for laptops, OS/2
was not well set up. We have to broaden its appeal,' Walker said.
Reports that development of the slimmed-down and PowerPC OS/2 versions
are late are inaccurate, he added.
Walker said OS/2 for IBM PCs based on the PowerPC chip will only be
available in 'late beta' stage when the machines ship later this year.
COMPUTING 7/7/94 P13

