Ballmer, executive VP of sales and support at the Redmond, Wash.,
software giant, told a meeting of financial analysts July 21. 'And it
will likely be April before we collect the first revenue from Chicago'.
'You have to conclude that the growth of the PC industry - and,
therefore, Microsoft - will slow,' says Ballmer. Adds chairman and CEO
Bill Gates, 'We're investing in the future and are very cautious about
short-term prospects.'
The wild card is Chicago, also known as Windows 4.0, which Microsoft
hopes will spark another upgrade cycle and expand its revenue stream.
That won't happen, of course, until Chicago is in stores. 'Sounds to me
like Chicago won't ship until the April-to-June period,' says Neil
Weintraut, an analyst at Hambrecht & Quist Inc., a securities brokerage
